data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It's completely removed.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown** — that `catch` block is dead code.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`**.

### Why It Was Removed

`Thread.Abort()` was inherently unsafe — it could fire *between any two IL instructions*, corrupting locks, leaving `finally` blocks unrun, and leaking resources. The .NET team removed it with no replacement by design.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask Stop(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false)
        await _cts.CancelAsync();

        // Wait with a hard timeout (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)))
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log it, but do NOT force-kill.
            // There is no safe equivalent to Thread.Abort().
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within {Timeout}", timeout);
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking `GetNextItem()` can't be cancelled** | If your original method blocks on a `Queue` or socket, you *must* refactor it to accept a `CancellationToken` (e.g., `Channel<T>.ReadAsync(token)`). Without this, `Stop()` will hang. |
| **No force-kill equivalent** | There is no safe replacement for `Thread.Abort()`. Design for cooperative cancellation instead. If you wrap unmanaged/third-party blocking code, isolate it in a separate **process** (not thread) that you can kill. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` silently becomes dead code** | The code compiles but never executes. If your rollback logic was critical, it's now silently lost — move it to `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | It doesn't wake up blocked threads. `CancellationToken` integrates with `async` APIs, `WaitHandle`, and `Semaphore` to interrupt waits. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in Stop()** | Replace with `await Task.WhenAny(...)` — non-blocking timeout that doesn't burn a thread. |

### If You Can't Make `GetNextItem` Async

Wrap the synchronous blocking call so cancellation still works:

```csharp
private async Task<Item> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Runs blocking call on thread pool, but cancellation
    // only checks between iterations — not mid-block.
    return await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(), token);
}
```

> ⚠️ This only cancels *before* the delegate starts. If `GetNextItem()` is already blocking, it won't interrupt it. The real fix is to migrate to `Channel<T>`, `BlockingCollection.Take(CancellationToken)`, or async I/O.

### Recommended: Use `BackgroundService` (Host Integration)

If this runs in an ASP.NET Core or Generic Host app:

```csharp
public class ItemProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}

// Registration:
builder.Services.AddHostedService<ItemProcessor>();
```

This gives you lifecycle management, graceful shutdown, and DI integration for free.
